'''''Diablo Immortal''''' is an upcoming [[action role-playing]] [[hack and slash]] video game in the [[Diablo (series)|''Diablo'' series]] designed for [[massively multiplayer online|online multiplayer]] play on mobile devices. Developed by [[Blizzard Entertainment|Blizzard]] and [[NetEase]], the game was announced in late 2018 and is planned for release on [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]] with no set release date.

== Gameplay ==

''Diablo Immortal'' is a [[massively multiplayer online]] [[action game]] in the [[Diablo (series)|''Diablo'' series]] designed for play on mobile devices.{{r|Verge: full-fledged}}<!-- hack n slash goes here --> The fast-paced{{r|Polygon: not for me}} ''Immortal'' is set between the events of ''Diablo 2'' and ''Diablo 3'',{{r|Polygon: reskin}} and borrows the look and feel of the latter.{{r|Polygon: not for me}} 

The game is designed for a touchscreen, with virtual controls that overlay the display: a directional thumbstick and ability buttons. The player can aim the ability by holding its button.{{r|Polygon: not for me}} Each of the six character classes—Barbarian, Wizard, Monk, Necromancer, Demon Hunter, and Crusader{{r|Polygon: reskin}}—have four abilities,{{r|Kotaku: preview}} which differ across character classes. For example, the Barbarian's class abilities include a slamming hammer and turning into a whirlwind. The Wizard casts a beam of electricity that boomerangs back to its source, dealing damage twice.{{r|Polygon: not for me}} Skills generally aim towards the nearest enemy.{{r|Kotaku: preview}} Blizzard plans for each class to have 12 unlockable skills, from which the player choose five to use concurrently.{{r|Kotaku: preview}}

Defeated enemies drop items ("loot") that can be equipped via a pop-up button.{{r|Kotaku: preview}} Players can join and leave groups that play through "dynamic events".{{r|Verge: full-fledged}} Unlike other ''Diablo'' series games, in the ''Immortal'' preview, the mana resource is removed and newly equipped items do not change the visual appearance of the player's character.{{r|Kotaku: preview}}

== Development ==

''Immortal'' is co-developed by Blizzard and NetEase.{{r|Verge: full-fledged}} The latter developer had been Blizzard's partner for Chinese market releases.{{r|Polygon: reskin}} Blizzard intended to bring the core ''Diablo'' experience to the smartphone platform. As a result, its interfaces reflect choices that would make that experience best fit the medium.{{r|Polygon: response}} By designing for a smartphone gaming audience, ''Immortal'' was designed to reach demographics and geographic regions that use mobile phones as their main gaming platform and may not otherwise interact with ''Diablo'' on other gaming platforms.{{r|Polygon: response}}

The game is planned for release on [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]] platforms.{{r|Polygon: reskin}} No release date is set.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Welsh |first1=Oli |title=There's an all-new Diablo game called Diablo Immortal |work=[[Eurogamer]] |date=2018-11-02 |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-11-02-theres-an-all-new-diablo-game-called-diablo-immortal |language=en |accessdate=2018-11-04 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Players can pre-register on the game's website for admission to [[playtest]] the [[beta release|beta]].{{r|Verge: full-fledged}} Blizzard also announced plans to keep the ''Immortal'' experience fresh after its initial release with the regular addition of stories and characters.{{r|Verge: full-fledged}} The game was announced at the opening ceremony of BlizzCon in November 2018.

==Reception==
====Pre-release====
The announcement's response was largely negative.{{r|Polygon: response}} While traditional gaming audiences often express skepticism towards diluted mobile versions of a cherished franchise, the ''Diablo'' series community's discontent was compounded by their anticipation for a larger announcement.{{r|Polygon: reskin|Polygon: response}} They expressed their discontent through online channels, likening ''Immortal'' to a reskin of one of NetEase's prior games, ''Crusaders of Light''.{{r|Polygon: reskin}} Blizzard responded that ''Immortal'' is but one ''Diablo'' series game in active development, and pointed to the company's multi-platform development experience and the success of the mobile version of ''[[Hearthstone (video game)|Hearthstone]]''  as evidence of Blizzard's capacity to overcome uncertainty and do right by their core audience.{{r|Polygon: response}} Blizzard also debunked a rumor that they had withheld announcement of a main ''Diablo'' sequel due to the negative response at ''Immortal''{{'}}s reveal; Blizzard stated "we didn’t pull any announcements from BlizzCon this year or have plans for other announcements. We do continue to have different teams working on multiple unannounced Diablo projects, and we look forward to announcing when the time is right."{{r|IGN: withholding}}.

After the reveal at [[BlizzCon]], developers participated in a Q&A with attendees. Two particular questions leveled at Wyatt Cheng, Principal Game Designer at Blizzard, drew significant attention from media and audiences alike, with one attendee asking if the announcement was an "out of season [[April Fools']] joke"<ref>{{cite web|author=Joseph Knoop|url=https://www.dailydot.com/parsec/diablo-immortal/|title=‘Is this an April Fools joke?’ Blizzard fans are having a fit over the new Diablo mobile game|publisher=The Daily Dot|date=November 3, 2018|accessdate=2018-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Eli Becht|title=WATCH: Fan Asks If Diablo: Immortal Is April Fool's Joke
|url=https://heavy.com/games/2018/11/diablo-immortal-april-fools-joke/|publisher=Heavy.com|date=November 2, 2018|accessdate=2018-11-13}}</ref>, and another if it there was a possibility for a PC release, leading to the crowd [[booing]] when the answer was negative.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ben Kuchera |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/5/18064290/blizzard-diablo-immortal-reaction-explainer-blizzcon|title=Diablo: Immortal broke the unspoken rules of Blizzard, and BlizzCon
|publisher=Polygon|date=November 5, 2018|accessdate=2018-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Asif Khan |url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/108310/fans-react-to-diablo-immortal-like-disrespectful-edgelords-at-blizzcon-2018s-qa|title=Fans react to Diablo Immortal like disrespectful edgelords at BlizzCon 2018's Q&A|publisher=ShackNews|date=November 2, 2018|accessdate=2018-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Robert Workman |url=https://comicbook.com/gaming/2018/11/04/diablo-immortal-angry-fans-blizzard/|title='Diablo Immortal' Gets Heavy Ire From Die-Hard Blizzard Fans|publisher=ComicBook.com|date=November 4, 2018|accessdate=2018-11-13}}</ref>

Following the announcent, Activision Blizzard's stock fell 7% on the first weekday of trading.<ref>{{cite web|author=Paul Tassi |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/insertcoin/2018/11/06/diablo-immortal-blizzcon-backlash-leads-to-activision-stock-slide/|title='Diablo Immortal' BlizzCon Backlash Leads To Activision Stock Slide|publisher=Forbes|date=November 6, 2018|accessdate=2018-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Keith Noonan |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2018/11/11/fans-hate-activision-blizzards-newest-game-should.aspx|title=Fans Hate Activision Blizzard's Newest Game. Should Investors Be Worried?|publisher=The Motley Fool|date=November 11, 2018|accessdate=2018-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Haydn Taylor |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-11-06-activision-blizzard-stocks-tumble-amid-fan-backlash-over-diablo-immortal|title=Activision Blizzard stock tumbles following Diablo Immortal backlash|publisher=GameIndustry.biz|date=November 6, 2018|accessdate=2018-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Eddie Makuch |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/activision-blizzard-stock-drops-following-diablo-d/1100-6463046/|title=Activision Blizzard Stock Drops Following Diablo Drama At BlizzCon|publisher=GameSpot|date=November 5, 2018|accessdate=2018-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Richard Scott-Jones |url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/diablo-immortal-stock-crash
|title=Activision-Blizzard’s stock crashes 7% after Diablo: Immortal Reveal|publisher=PCGamesN|date=November 6, 2018|accessdate=2018-11-13}}</ref>

Previews of the game's demo approved of the game's controls,{{r|Polygon: not for me|Kotaku: preview}} its interface having been tested by prior NetEase games,{{r|Kotaku: preview}} <!--While ''Kotaku'' described the controls as intuitive and occasionally slow,{{r|Kotaku: preview}}-->though ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]''{{'s}} reviewer noted difficulties in precision controls.<!--with ranged classes?-->{{r|Polygon: not for me}} The locked abilities made some character classes less enjoyable to play, as the Wizard's ability cooldown timers made the class less effective in groups.{{r|Kotaku: preview}}

Demo reviewers felt that where ''Immortal'' captured the series' look and feel, it omitted some of its core tenets,{{r|Polygon: not for me|Kotaku: preview}} or as ''Polygon'' put it, ''Diablo''{{'s}} "soul".{{r|Polygon: not for me}} Whereas the mobile game captured the basic Diablo experience, the reviewers questioned whether the new entry had enough new content to remain fresh.{{r|Polygon: not for me|Kotaku: preview}}<!-- enough to warrant the transition to imprecise hardware.{{r|Polygon: not for me}}--><!--Journalists noted similarities between the game's user interface and that of free-to-play mobile game ''Crusaders of Light'' (2017) by [[NetEase]]. The developer collaborates with Blizzard to release the latter's games in China.{{r|Polygon: reskin}}-->

