{{Infobox Instrument |name=Udukku |image=Udukku.jpg |image_capt=Udukku (Udukkai) |background= |names= |classification= *[[Percussion instrument|Percussion]] |range= |hornbostel_sachs= |hornbostel_sachs_desc= |related= *[[Damaru]] *[[Edakka]] }}
The '''Udukku''', also known as ''Udukkai'',({{Lang-ta|உடுக்கை}}) ({{Lang-ml|ഉടുക്ക്}}) , is an Indian traditional percussion instrument of [[Dravidian peoples|dravidian]] origin, once popular in [[Tamil Nadu]] [[Kerala]], and north and east parts of [[Sri Lanka]], similar to [[Damaru]] and [[Edakka]], larger than the former but smaller than the latter. [[File:An Udukkai 2.JPG|thumb|left|An Udukku]] {{Indian music}}
== Profile == [[File:Udukku.resized.jpg|thumb|240px|left|Udukku]] Udukku is a smaller version of [[Edakka]], shaped like an hour glass.<ref name="Milapfest">{{cite web | url=http://www.milapfest.com/instruments-india/explore-instruments/the-udukkai/ | title=Milapfest | publisher=Milapfest | date=2014 | accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref> The instrument is about 8 to 10 inches long with a girth of 6 to 8 inches on both ends and tapering towards the centre.<ref name="Nathalaya">{{cite web | url=http://www.nathalaya.co.uk/instruments/percussion/udukku | title=Nathalaya | publisher=Nathalaya | date=2014 | accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref><ref name="India 9">{{cite web | url=http://www.india9.com/i9show/Udukku-66020.htm | title=India 9 | publisher=India 9 | date=2014 | accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref> The body of the instrument is traditionally made out of kiln fired clay but later variants are made of wood, preferebly from a single hollow block of Jackfruit wood. Brass bodies are also used in some parts.<ref name="Milapfest" /> The ends of the instrument is covered across the mouth with cured and dried animal hide, goat skin is the preferred leather. Hoops are placed on the edge of the instrument body and the skin is tightened using strings woven from end to end.<ref name="Milapfest" /> Udukku is played on one side and the non playing side is provided with one or two metallic wire snares, enabling the player to generate more resonance. A strap made of cloth is fixed to the middle of the instrument for clasping it. Coloured balls made of cotton strings are also placed hanging from the instrument as an embellishment.<ref name="Nathalaya" />
Udukku is commonly played as the percussion accompaniment in temple rituals or in folk culture.<ref name="India 9" /> The ''Ayyappan Pattu'' performed at [[Sabarimala]] temple in Kerala to propitiate [[Lord Ayyappa]], uses Udukku as the percussion accompaniment<ref name="Udukku Chandai">{{cite AV media | url=https://www.amazon.com/Udukku-Chandai/dp/B0019TRPAY | title=Ayyappan Arputhangal | publisher=Geethanjali | date=2006 | medium=Music album | ASIN=B0019TRPAY}}</ref> and is often called ''Udukku Pattu''.<ref name="India Video">{{cite web | url=http://www.indiavideo.org/kerala/arts/ritual-art-forms/ayyappan-paattu-74.php | title=India Video | publisher=India Video | date=2014 | accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref> ''Udukku Kotti Pattu'', is a traditional art form of Kerala where the vocal rendition of the song is accompanied by the Udukku rhythms.<ref name="Chendamelam">{{cite web | url=http://www.chendamelam.net/udukkupattu.html | title=Chendamelam | publisher=Chendamelam | date=2014 | accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Udukku Kotti Pattu">{{cite web | url=http://traditionsinkerala.blogspot.ae/2014/01/udukku-kotti-pattu-folk-song.html | title=Udukku Kotti Pattu | publisher=Traditions in Kerala | date=17 January 2014 | accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref> It has been reported that Udukku was popular in [[Jafna]], Sri Lanka even during the 9th century AD.<ref name="Google Book">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k9DpMY206bMC&pg=PA174&lpg=PA174&dq=Udukku+musical+instrument&source=bl&ots=5_jTDM_P41&sig=r2NnfRH5We8nBqOi1i2LhE8r2t0&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Z41rVK4Midc8mviBkAM&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Udukku%20musical%20instrument&f=false | title=Ancient Jaffna: Being a Research Into the History of Jaffna from Very Early Times to the Portug[u]ese Period | publisher=Asian Educational Services | author=C. Rasanayagam | year=1926 | pages=390 | isbn=9788120602106}}</ref>
== Playing style == Udukku is played holding it horizontally, only on one side, generally the right side, while the left hand is used to clasp the instrument with the cloth strap.<ref name="India 9" /> The fingers, mainly index, middle and ring fingers, along with the inner palm are used for playing and the cloth strap is squeezed or released to adjust the tightness of the leather to attain pitch modulation.<ref name="India 9">{{cite web | url=http://www.india9.com/i9show/Udukku-66020.htm | title=India 9 | publisher=India 9 | date=2014 | accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref> Fingers of the left hand are also used to adjust the tightness by pulling the strings directly.<ref name="Nathalaya" />
== Well-known performers == * Kaliyamoorthy Poosari<ref name="Spotify">{{cite web | url=https://open.spotify.com/album/6MPZdZlqszwve5EjLrZlOl | title=Spotify | publisher=Spotify | date=2014 | accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref> * Karivelil Radhakrishnan<ref name="Radhakrishnan">{{cite web | url=http://www.muziekjes.nl/karivelil-radhakrishnan-an-udukku-exponent-part-1-11217753-song.html | title=Radhakrishnan | publisher=Muziekjez | date=2014 | accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Q4Music">{{cite web | url=http://q4music.blogspot.ae/2010/11/karivelil-radhakrishnan-udukku-exponent_25.html | title=Q4Music | publisher=Q4Music | date=2014 | accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref>
